system_model:
Consider an OFDM system with $K=64$ subcarriers. The transmitted signal on subcarrier $k$ is denoted as $X[k] \in \mathbb{C}$, where $k = 0, 1, \ldots, K-1$. The frequency-domain channel response is $H[k] \in \mathbb{C}$, and the received signal is given by:
\begin{equation}
Y[k] = H[k] \cdot X[k] + N[k]
\end{equation}
where $N[k] \sim \mathcal{CN}(0, \sigma^2)$ is complex Gaussian noise. A comb-type pilot pattern is employed with $P=16$ pilots uniformly spaced every 4th subcarrier at positions $\mathcal{P} = \{0, 4, 8, \ldots, 60\}$. The least squares (LS) channel estimate at pilot positions is:
\begin{equation}
\hat{H}_{\text{LS}}[k_p] = \frac{Y[k_p]}{X[k_p]}, \quad k_p \in \mathcal{P}
\end{equation}
Linear interpolation extends these pilot estimates to all $K$ subcarriers, yielding the initial estimate $\hat{\mathbf{h}}_{\text{LS}} \in \mathbb{C}^K$.

problem_statement:
The objective is to learn a complex-valued denoising diffusion model that estimates the channel vector $\mathbf{h} \in \mathbb{C}^K$ from noisy pilot observations. The model is trained to minimize the denoising score matching objective:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}(\theta) = \mathbb{E}_{t \sim \mathcal{U}[1,T], \mathbf{h}_0 \sim p_{\text{data}}, \boldsymbol{\epsilon} \sim \mathcal{CN}(\mathbf{0}, \mathbf{I})} \left[ \left\| \boldsymbol{\epsilon} - \boldsymbol{\epsilon}_\theta(\mathbf{h}_t, t) \right\|^2 \right]
\end{equation}
where $\mathbf{h}_t = \sqrt{\bar{\alpha}_t} \mathbf{h}_0 + \sqrt{1 - \bar{\alpha}_t} \boldsymbol{\epsilon}$ is the noised channel at timestep $t$, and $\|\mathbf{z}\|^2 = \sum_{k=0}^{K-1} |z_k|^2$ is the complex squared norm. The denoiser $\boldsymbol{\epsilon}_\theta$ employs a novel Phase Interaction Layer that decomposes the prediction into amplitude and phase components:
\begin{equation}
\hat{\epsilon}_k = a_k \cdot e^{j\phi_k} = a_k \cos(\phi_k) + j \cdot a_k \sin(\phi_k)
\end{equation}
where $a_k = \text{Softplus}(f_a(\mathbf{z}))_k \geq 0$ and $\phi_k = f_\phi(\mathbf{z})_k \in \mathbb{R}$.

